<br>
FoS means you can't be persecuted for what you say or believe, provided you aren't actively seeking to hurt other people or inciting violence.<br>
<br>
However, FoS does NOT mean you are granted an audience.  If people attend a speech by the President, FoS does not give you the right to disrupt that speech.  People came to hear the President, not you, and they have a right to hear who they want to hear.<br>
<br>
FoS does NOT mean you are granted a stage for your words, either.  If you want to be heard, then YOU are responsible for building your own stage, not taking over someone else's.<br>
<br>
If *I* build a stage, *I* have the right to decide who gets to talk, what they get to talk about, and what sort of language is acceptable.  And if I choose to disallow certain conversations or certain words, that's fully within my rights as the owner of the stage.  If you don't like the rules, you are certainly free to build your own stage.<br>
<br>
Now, if I somehow managed to acquire all the stages and held a monopoly, plus managed to keep you from building your own stage, then you could get a lawyer and wave the constitution at me.<br>
<br>
These message boards are in no way a monopoly.  You don't like the rules here, go build your own stage.<br>
<br>
I've also gotten extremely tired of people calling this &quot;censorship&quot; as if it's evil.  It's censorship when the FCC tells TV stations they can't use certain words over the air.  It's censorship when those stations decide to not broadcast certain types of shows during prime child-watching hours.  It's censorship when parents can lock down their cable tuners to keep their children from watching naughty shows.<br>
<br>
I don't see anyone who thinks there's anything wrong with the above.<br>
<br>
Censorship is wrong when it prevents FoS, when it prevents people from expressing themselves in any environment where they could be heard.  It's wrong when it prevents dissenting opinion from being heard, or even a specific dissenting voice, provided that voice can follow reasonable rules of expression.<br>
<br>
As used on these boards, I have not seen one single instance of censorship that actually prevents anyone from saying what they want to say in a reasonable fashion.<br>
